ween a beneficent environment and intensive cultivation ultimately became threatening to the soil and exploitative of the people who worked it.Invoking history, economics, sociology, agriculture, and environmental studies, Stoll traces the often tragic repercussions of fruit farming and shows how central this story is to the development of the industrial countryside in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectszCalifornia. 0aFruit tradezCalifornia. 0aFruitzCaliforniaxMarketing. 0aHorticulturezCalifornia. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  aagriculture.  aamerican west.  acalifornia growers.  acalifornia.  acapitalism.  acitrus.  acoastal plains.  acultivation.  aeconomics.  aenvironmental impact.  aenvironmental studies.  afarming.  afood and agriculture.  afood studies.  afrontier.  afruit farming.  afruit industry.  afruit production.  afruit.  ahistory.  aindustrial countryside.  aland development.  anonfiction.  aproduce.  arural.  asettling the west.  asociology.  asoil studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092020040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520920200423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520920200/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY